.env
# Virtual environment: contains installed packages for local development
# - What: Python virtual environment files (pip-installed site-packages, binaries)
# - Why ignore: large, machine-specific, reproducible from `requirements.txt`
# - Size: often 10s-100s MB depending on packages
# - Who/When: generated by developer when creating venv (e.g., `python -m venv .venv`)
.venv

# Environment variable files: local secret config
# - What: API keys, DB credentials, secrets used for local dev
# - Why ignore: contains sensitive information that must not be committed
# - Size: tiny (bytes), but high sensitivity
.env

# Compiled Python artifacts
# - What: interpreter bytecode and caches generated during runtime or tests
# - Why ignore: derived files, platform-specific, unnecessary for source control
# - Size: typically small per file (KBs) but can accumulate
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]

# Jupyter notebook checkpoints
# - What: automatic savepoints created by Jupyter (hidden folder)
# - Why ignore: noisy auto-saves, not source; notebooks themselves may be committed
# - Size: small per checkpoint, can clutter history
.ipynb_checkpoints/

# Project dataset(s)
# - `movies_metadata.csv`: movie dataset used for recommendations/experiments
# - What: CSV export of movie metadata (titles, overviews, genres, release dates, etc.)
# - Why ignore: large sample datasets and user-provided data should not bloat repo; data may be redownloadable from source or stored in a data/ folder outside VCS
# - Size: typically from a few MB up to 100s of MB depending on dataset and exports; treat as large binary/text asset
# - Who/When: obtained by the project author (downloaded once), updated when re-exporting the dataset
/movies_metadata.csv

# Local temporary files and drafts
# - `temp/` contains working drafts like `latex.md`, `resume.md` and other transient notes
# - What: personal drafts, intermediate artifacts, exported docs used during development
# - Why ignore: these are not part of the application codebase and may contain personal info or irrelevant content
# - Size: typically small (KBs), but may include generated artifacts later
temp/

# Markdown files: ignore all Markdown notes and drafts except the main project README
# - What: auxiliary documentation, notes, proofs-of-concept, or exported docs
# - Why ignore: keep repository documentation surface minimal (keep README.md tracked). Other .md files are often drafts or personal notes and clutter history.
# - Size: small per file (KBs), but many files add noise and merge conflicts
*.md
!README.md

# Byte-distribution / packaging metadata
# - Wheel/pip build metadata and caches generated when building packages
# - Why ignore: derived packaging artifacts
pip-wheel-metadata/
*.egg-info/

# Editor/IDE and OS files
# - What: local editor settings, workspace files, OS metadata
# - Why ignore: machine-specific, noisy, not relevant to other contributors
# - Examples for this project: VS Code settings, macOS .DS_Store
.vscode/
.DS_Store

# Test and coverage caches
# - What: pytest cache, coverage reports, temporary test output
# - Why ignore: generated during CI/local testing; not source
.pytest_cache/
coverage/

# Node/Python packaging lock or build (if used transiently)
# - Why ignore: generated build artifacts, ephemeral
dist/
build/

# Notes:
# - Rules above are tailored to this repository (movie-rec-main). We explicitly ignore
#   `temp/` because it holds draft markdown files present in the workspace (e.g.,
#   temp/latex.md, temp/resume.md) that are personal and unrelated to the app.
# - We ignore `movies_metadata.csv` because the dataset is large, can be obtained
#   externally, and committing it would bloat the repo and make clones slow.
# - We keep `README.md` tracked as the canonical project documentation; all other
#   Markdown files are ignored to avoid accidental commits of personal notes.

# Local virtual environment (alternate name used in this workspace)
# - What: `venv/` is a common venv folder (this repo currently has `venv/` present)
# - Why ignore: same reasons as `.venv` above — large, machine-specific, reproducible
# - Size: tens to 100s of MB depending on packages
venv/

# Precomputed model and data artifacts (pickles, numpy arrays, model weights)
# - What: files like `tfidf.pkl`, `tfidf_matrix.pkl`, `df.pkl`, `indices.pkl` in this repo
#   store fitted TF-IDF vectors, sparse matrices, serialized DataFrames, and index maps used
#   at runtime by `app.py`/`main.py` to serve recommendations.
# - Why ignore: these are derived/binary artifacts that can be large, platform-dependent,
#   and should be reproducible from source code and `movies_metadata.csv` or retraining.
# - Size: can range from a few KB (small indices) to 10s-100s MB (dense models, TF-IDF sparse matrices)
# - Note: if you want to keep a small sample artifact for CI or demos, consider a separate
#   releases bucket or a small committed sample under a dedicated folder.
*.pkl
*.npy
*.npz
*.npz
*.h5
*.pt
*.ckpt

# Logs, runtime databases, and checkpoints
# - What: runtime logs, SQLite DB files, training checkpoints
# - Why ignore: generated during runs or training; not source
*.log
*.sqlite3
*.db
logs/

# Model/weights directories often used by ML experiments
models/

# If you already committed any of the above large/binary files, they remain in git history
# until removed with `git rm --cached <file>` and a commit. Ask me if you want me to
# untrack `tfidf_matrix.pkl`, `tfidf.pkl`, `df.pkl`, `indices.pkl`, or `movies_metadata.csv`.